<HTML><head>
<title>Scientific American Editors' Selections</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<map  name="header">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="460,0,476,57" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/index.html#mainmenu">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="166,8,258,30" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/currentissue.html">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="168,31,257,50" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/explorations/">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,0,352,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/interview/">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="260,18,352,38" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/askexpert/">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="259,40,352,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/bookmarks/">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="352,0,442,18" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/marketplace/mrktindex.html">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,19,444,40" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/forms/editorletterform.html">

<AREA SHAPE="rect" COORDS="353,41,443,58" HREF="http://www.sciam.com/cgi-bin/search.cgi">
</map>
<A HREF="../cgi-bin/imagemap/chipheaderweb"><IMG ISMAP SRC="../graphics/chipheader.gif" usemap="#header" BORDER=0 WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="58"></A><BR><IMG SRC="../graphics/hangerbookmark.gif" WIDTH="476" HEIGHT="27"><P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE="6">E<FONT SIZE="5">DITORS'</FONT> S<FONT
SIZE="5">ELECTIONS</FONT> F<FONT SIZE="5">ROM THE</FONT> W<FONT
SIZE="5">EB</FONT></FONT><P></CENTER>





SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN's editors come across a steady stream of interesting,
informative, entertaining--and sometimes unexpected--sites on the World Wide
Web. We wanted to share with our readers some of our favorite locations.<P>

Like the Web itself, this feature is constantly growing and evolving. We
also appreciate feedback from our readers. If you have a favorite science-
or technology-related site that does not appear here, <A
HREF="mailto:cpowell@sciam.com">send us the URL</A> and we
may add it to our list.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<CENTER>
<TABLE>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#a"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Science News</A></TD>   
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#g"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Chemistry</A></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#b"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Amateur Scientist</A></TD>   


<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#i"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Materials</A></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#c"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Archaeology And Paleontology</A></TD>        <TD valign=baseline
><A HREF="#j"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Mathematics</A></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#d"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Astronomy And Astrophysics</A></TD>  <TD valign=baseline
><A HREF="#k"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Museums</A></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#e"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP
WIDTH="14" HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Biology And Medicine</A></TD>        
<TD valign=baseline><A
HREF="#l"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Government Institutions</A></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="#f"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Earth And Environment</A></TD>  
<TD valign=baseline><A
HREF="#m"><IMG SRC="../graphics/arrowsmall.gif" ALIGN=TOP WIDTH="14"
HEIGHT="13" BORDER="0"> Searching The Web</A></TD></TR>
<TR>
        
</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>




<HR SIZE=4>





<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=2 CELLSPACING=2>

<TR>
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=4><A NAME="a"><B>SCIENCE NEWS</B></A></TD>       
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://whyfiles.news.wisc.edu/">The Why Files</A>, a project of the
National Institute for Science Education, offers well-researched and clearly
written investigations of current topics in science. A new story is posted
every other week, and the site also includes a small but worthy collection
of scientific images.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.utdallas.edu/research/issues/">Issues
in Science and Technology</A> is the policy journal of The National Academy
of Sciences. This site offers selections from the journal, along with
pointers to other online science publications and resources.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://pao.gsfc.nasa.gov/gsfc/newsroom/flash/flash.htm">FLASH</A> is a
list of breaking news stories from NASA: information on current and upcoming
missions, the latest images from space and related press releases.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.het.brown.edu/news/index.html">Physics
News</A> is maintained by the high-energy physics department at Brown
University; it contains a neat roundup of the top stories in the field and
links to more information.<P></TD></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=2><A NAME="b"><B>AMATEUR SCIENTIST</B></A></TD>      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.thesphere.com/sas/SciAm/SciAm.html">The Amateur
Scientist</A> is an electronic companion to the column in Scientific
American. It contains a complete index to "The Amateur Scientist" and a
collection of additional online resources; it is part of a very extensive
site maintained by the Society for Amateur Scientists.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://sulcus.berkeley.edu/FLM/SH/MDL/Invention/Invention.Masterlist.html">Invention
Master Resource List</A>--a place where home-grown inventors can search
patent databases, learn how to raise capital, get in touch with other
inventors, etc.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="c"><B>ARCHAEOLOGY AND PALEONTOLOGY</B></A></TD>   
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://ucmp1.berkeley.edu/"> UC Museum of Paleontology</A></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://tyrrell.magtech.ab.ca/index.html">Royal
Tyrrell Museum</A></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://denr1.igis.uiuc.edu:/isgsroot/dinos/GIFs_path.html">DINO RUSS's
collection of dinosaur images</A></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.dinosauria.com/">Dinosauria
On-line</A></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.lib.uconn.edu/ArchNet/">ArchNet --
beautifully designed and organized guide to archaeology resources</A><P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://nautarch.tamu.edu/nappr.htm">Nautical
Archaeology projects</A><P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="d"><B>ASTRONOMY AND ASTROPHYSICS</B></A></TD>     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/astropix.html">Astronomy Picture of
the Day</A> is brief and informative. Each image is accompanied by a
one-paragraph explanation, with key terms linked to definitions. All past
images are held in a searchable archive.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.stsci.edu/public.html">The Hubble Space
Telescope</A>'s public information office maintains an extensive, constantly
updated collection of stunning images and movies from the orbiting
observatory; the site also contains press releases and other explanatory
texts.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://bang.lanl.gov/solarsys/homepage.htm">Views
of the Solar System</A> delivers what its name promises: a great virtual
tour of the sun, planets, satellites, comets and asteroids, including
in-depth information about every body mentioned.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://ccf.arc.nasa.gov:80/sst/">Asteroid and
Comet Impact Hazards</A> gives the straight facts on what would happen if an
asteroid or comet were to strike the earth. There are also pointers to
relevant images, scientific findings and policy developments.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://jean-luc.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Exhibits/">Numerical
Relativity Exhibitions</A> are maintained by the Relativity Group at the
National Center for Supercomputing Applications. The site includes computer
graphics and animations that portray the mind-bending world of black holes
and Einsteinian relativity.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/htmltest/rjn_bht.html">Virtual Trips to
Black Holes and Neutron Stars</A>. Robert Nemiroff of the NASA-Goddard Space
Flight Center has created a virtual environment in which the user can
witness firsthand the bizarre ways the laws of physics behave around these
objects.</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=8><A NAME="e"><B>BIOLOGY AND MEDICINE</B></A><P></TD>        
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://phylogeny.arizona.edu/tree/phylogeny.html">The Tree of Life</A>
traces the branching classification that shows the relationships between all
living organisms. Users can navigate their way up the tree or search
directly for a given taxonomic classification; illustrations and references
enrich the trip.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.life.uiuc.edu/Entomology/insectgifs.html">Insect
Drawings at Illinois</A> comes from the archive of the University of
Illinois. This vast collection of insect illustrations serves as a visual
overview of the various orders of insects, but they can equally well be
enjoyed as fine art.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://cvs.anu.edu.au/andy/beye/beyehome.html">B-EYE</A> opens up a
whole new vista: the world as seen through the eyes of a honeybee.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.comet.chv.va.us/quill/">CELLS
alive!</A> maintains an intriguing collection of images and animations of
microscopic life; the site is organized into mini-essays. Despite the name,
there are also some non-biological images here.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.bocklabs.wisc.edu/virusviztop.html">Visualizations of
Viruses</A> offers a collection of computer-rendered, false-colored images
of virus particles. Who knew the polio virus was so beautiful? Serious
researchers can generate custom-tailed images "on the fly."<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
      

<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.pbrc.hawaii.edu/%7Ekunkel/">Dennis Kunkel's Microscopy</A>
displays an array of images showing the living world--insects, cells,
biological molecules--as it appears at high magnification.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/research/visible/visible_human.html">The
Visible Human Project</A> is supporting research to develop comprehensive,
three-dimensional images of the human body. The project's web site includes
cross-sectional views of the body and pointers to various medical
visualizations.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.ornl.gov/TechResources/Human_Genome/home.html">Human
Genome Project Information</A> is the creation of Oak Ridge National
Laboratory. The site includes all of the latest news from the project, along
with various educational resources.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="f"><B>EARTH AND ENVIRONMENT</B></A><P></TD>       
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.fourmilab.ch/earthview/vplanet.html">Earth Viewer</A> is a
slow but fascinating site. It allows you to create interactive views of the
earth from any vantage point in space; here is your chance to watch the sun
set from the space shuttle. The site also offers access to interactive
planetary and sky maps.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://wxp.atms.purdue.edu/">WXP</A> offers a
comprehensive and intelligently packaged collection of current U.S. weather
images, climatological data and forecasts.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www-bprc.mps.ohio-state.edu/">Byrd Polar
Research Center</A> contains a diversity of information and images
concerning all research polar or ice related; there is even a peek into the
past, via the ancient climate records locked in ice cores.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://edcwww.cr.usgs.gov/dclass/dclass.html">The
EROS Data Center</A>, a part of the U.S. Geological Survey, is distributing
declassified intelligence photos. This is the entry point for those who want
to sample these spoils of the Cold War. <P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.ucar.edu/">University Corporation for
Atmospheric Research</A> (UCAR) has created an abundant source for all kinds
of weather information and predictions. UCARweb also contains background information
on climate and environmental issues.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vw.html">VolcanoWorld</A> may look a
little silly at first, but there is intelligence just below the surface. The
site includes essays on volcanic processes and pointers to lots of images;
just be prepared to dig around a little.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=3><A NAME="g"><B>CHEMISTRY</B></A><P></TD>   
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.shef.ac.uk/%7Echem/web-elements/">WebElements</A> is an
interactive periodic table, the most sophisticated of its kind. Point and
click for remarkably detailed information about the element of your choice.
(Warning: it may tell you more than you really wanted to know.)<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://mwanal.lanl.gov/julie/imagemap/periodic/periodic.html">Periodic
Table of the Elements</A>, a product of Los Alamos National Laboratory,
provides basic information on the history, properties and uses of each of
the elements.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.csc.fi/lul/chem/graphics.html">Chemist's Art Gallery</A>
gives visual substance to the often abstract world of chemistry. Many of the
topics are rather abstract, but some of the computer renderings are
spectacular and the site includes an exhaustive list of related links, some
of them quite wonderful in their own right.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="i"><B>MATERIALS</B></A><P></TD>   
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://geology.wisc.edu/%7Ejill/image.html">Gem and Gemology Image
Gallery</A> shows over a dozen varieties of gemstones in both raw and
cut-and-polished form. Outline descriptions (clearly intended for a college
course) and occasional videos round out the site.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://galaxy.einet.net/images/gems/gems-icons.html">Smithsonian Gem &
Mineral Collection</A> displays highlights of one of the Smithsonian
Institution's remarkable holdings--even the Hope Diamond can be seen
here.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/index.html">Molecular
Expressions</A> maintains a dizzying array of exquisite photomicrographs.
The materials examined are a diverse lot, including beer, buckyballs and
silicon chips.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.att.com/microscapes/microscapes.html">AT&T's Microscapes
Gallery</A> showcases an exhibit of museum-quality micrographs, made using a
number of devices and techniques. The images mostly depict materials used in
modern information technologies.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.almaden.ibm.com/vis/stm/gallery.html">STM Image Gallery</A>
from IBM showcases the capability of the scanning tunneling microscope, a
device that takes microscopy to the limit by revealing individual atoms. The
images are neatly arranged in a virtual gallery space.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nas.nasa.gov/NAS/Education/nanotech/nanotech.html">Small is
Beautiful</A>, contrary to its name, is not much to look at. Rather, it
consists of a definitive set of links to online nanotechnology resources
(many of which do contain stunning images). When a better molecular machine
is invented, you will be able to find out about it here.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="j"><B>MATHEMATICS</B></A><P></TD> 
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://aleph0.clarku.edu/%7Edjoyce/julia/explorer.html">Mandelbrot and
Julia Set Explorer</A> is an interactive program that allows the user to
zoom through the basic forms of fractal geometry. Like the sets themselves,
the site is potentially infinite in extent.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www-chaos.umd.edu/gallery.html">Chaos
Gallery</A> at the University of Maryland can function as an introduction to
chaos study, or simply as a collection of intriguing, abstract forms. There
is something strangely soothing about these psychedelic mathematical
images.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.mta.ca/%7Errosebru/kbl/knotlinks.html">Knot a Braid</A> gives
weekly pointers to interesting mathematics sites on the Web, often ones with
noteworthy graphics. Warning: many of these require Java-capable browsers or
other advanced capabilities.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.geom.umn.edu:80/../graphics/">The Geometry
Center</A> at the University of Minnesota maintains a vast collection of
mathematically oriented images. A constantly changing featured image offers
a taste of what lies inside.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.fusebox.com/cb/alife.html/">Live
A-Life</A> is exactly what its name promises: a collection of artificial
life programs that you can download and activate on your computer. It is
sort of a digital-age version of sea monkeys, but there are also serious
scientific aspects to the programs. Note that this site requires a
frames-compatible browser.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.cbi.umn.edu/">The Charles Babbage
Institute</A> offers a tidy collection of articles and links relating to the
history of computers--and of course to Charles Babbage, the legendary
godfather of computing.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=6><A NAME="k"><B>MUSEUMS</B></A><P></TD>     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.si.edu/welcome/musovrvw/start.htm">Smithsonian
Institution</A>  site marks the entry point to the vast and varied parts of
the Smithsonian: 16 museums and galleries, the National Zoo and sundry
research facilities. Skip the guided tour--the opening screen tells you
everything you need to begin exploring. <P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nmsi.ac.uk/">The Science Museum,
London</A> conveys a British feel even on the Web. Floor maps and images
reside in the "collections and galleries" section.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.exploratorium.edu/">The San Francisco
Exploratorium</A> translates some of the museum's hands-on feel to the
electronic medium. The tutorials are aimed broadly at both parents and
children, the science-curious as well as educators.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://sln.fi.edu/">The Franklin Institute Science
Museum</A> augments online exhibits with news stories, hot links and other
useful resources.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.ucmp.berkeley.edu/">UC Museum of
Paleontology</A>, part of the University of California at Berkeley,
maintains one of the best life-sciences collections on the Internet. It
includes in-depth discussions of evolution and a detailed, illustrated tree
of life; the dinosaur section is outstanding. </TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
 
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.amnh.org/">American Museum of Natural
History</A> has a clean, elegant design that parallels the look and layout
of the museum's renovated halls of vertebrate evolution. The site may tax
the technological capabilities of those running slow connections or old Web
browsers, however. <P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=10><A NAME="l"><B>GOVERNMENT INSTITUTIONS</B></A><P></TD>     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nasa.gov/">National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</A> home page is the jumping-off point for space-related news
and for links to all of the NASA centers, including the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.esrin.esa.it/htdocs/esa/esa.html">European Space Agency</A>
is the European counterpart to NASA.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nsf.gov/">National Science
Foundation</A> presents science news and information for researchers and
educators.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nas.edu/">National Academy of
Sciences</A> site incorporates numerous pointers to books, journals and
breaking research.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nih.gov/">National Institutes of
Health</A> offers a useful starting point for finding health-related
information on the Web. <P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.who.ch/">World Health Organization</A>
surveys health issues around the globe.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.nist.gov/">National Institute of
Standards and Technology</A> supports both basic metrology work and
high-tech projects.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.doe.gov/">Department of Energy</A>
encompasses national laboratories, civilian energy programs and nuclear
defense production facilities; they can all be found under the "departmental
resources" heading.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.fda.gov/">Food and Drug
Administration</A> issues updates on food and drug safety and efficacy.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://lcweb.loc.gov/homepage/lchp.html">The
Library of Congress</A> is not just a huge book catalogue; it also posts
exhibits and supports THOMAS, the definitive source for complete text of
current Federal legislation.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
<TD valign=baseline rowspan=3><A NAME="m"><B>SEARCHING THE WEB</B></A><P></TD>   
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/DataSources/bySubject/Overview.html">WWW
Virtual Catalogue</A> is a staggeringly comprehensive compilation of
informational Web sites, arranged by topic<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
     
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://web.fie.com/www/us_gov.htm">WWW Virtual
Library</A> lists essentially all the major Federal Government Web
servers.<P></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
        
      
<TD valign=baseline><A HREF="http://www.vicnet.net.au/vicnet/garylist.html">VICNET</A> contains a
helpful list of tools for searching various parts of the Internet.<P></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


</BODY>
</HTML>



