<BR><BR><BR><BR><B><FONT SIZE=5>
We'd like to
<BR>hear from you.
<BR>Send us a 
<A HREF="../forms/editorletterform.html">letter</A>.</FONT></B></TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=340>

<P><table cellpadding=1 align=right width=145><tr>
<td><IMG SRC="IMG/0197letters.gif"" WIDTH="145" HEIGHT="184"
BORDER="1">
<FONT SIZE="1"> 
Photomontage: Patricia McDermond; 
Photographs: Courtesy of Photo Researchers, Inc </FONT>  <br clear=all></td>
</tr></table>

<I>The September single-topic issue, "What You Need to Know about Cancer,"
generated a considerable volume of mail from readers who have been touched
by the disease-physicians, patients, friends and family members. We offer
a sampling of responses.</I><HR>

<CENTER><B>TREATMENT OF PAIN</B></CENTER>

<P>You are to be commended for the excellent issue on cancer. Kathleen M.
Foley's article, "Controlling the Pain of Cancer," was right on target.
Having witnessed four family members painfully succumb to cancer, I
learned firsthand just how lacking the medical community and government
regulators are in their knowledge of pain control. Administering
pain-relieving medications without fear of overdose or addiction is
imperative to the comfort of the dying.

<P><I>EMILY CLEMENTS DOUCETTE Pompano Beach, Fla.</I>


<HR><CENTER><B>TAKING RESPONSIBILITY</B></CENTER>

<P>In "Cancer's Psychological Challenges," Jimmie C. Holland advises those
stricken with the disease, "Do not believe that you caused your cancer."
Although this may be good psychological advice, a "two packs a day" person
suffering from terminal lung cancer would have difficulty following it.
This patient's responsibility is clearly described in the lucid articles
"What Causes Cancer?," by Dimitrios Trichopoulos, Frederick P. Li and
David J. Hunter, and "Strategies for Minimizing Cancer Risk," by Walter C.
Willett, Graham A. Colditz and Nancy E. Mueller, both of which demonstrate
that the majority of cancers stem from preventable causes such as smoking
and poor diet.

<P><I>PETER E. SANDOR Toronto, Ontario</I>


<HR><CENTER><B>EARLY DETECTION</B></CENTER>

<P>How does one say thank you for the gift of early detection of colorectal
cancer, which led to my expeditious cure? I am 48 years old and hadn't had
a complete physical for five years: I was healthy and had a good family
history, so I thought physicals were unnecessary unless I was feeling
sick. I picked up your September issue at the airport to give to a friend
who has a family history of cancer. On the ight, I read the Editors' fact
sheet, "Twelve Major Cancers," about warning signs, detection and
diagnosis of cancer and realized that I had actually experienced some
minor, intermittent symptoms of colorectal cancer.

When I got home, I immediately made an appointment with my doctor, who
discovered a malignant polyp in my colon. Part of my colon was removed a
few days later; fortunately, the cancer had not spread. The doctors caught
the tumor before it spread because I went in early; I went in early
because I read your special issue. My heartfelt thanks to everyone who
worked on the project.

<P><I>C. JILL JONES Redwood City, Calif.</I>


<HR><CENTER><B>OBSTACLES AT THE FDA?</B></CENTER>

<P>In "What Are Obstacles to Ideal Care?," W. Wayt Gibbs wrote that "since
March, when the Food and Drug Administration announced that it was
lowering its efficacy standards for cancer drugs and clearing the backlog
of those awaiting approval, several new agents have made it to market."
Readers could gain the impression that efficacy standards for approval of
cancer drugs have been made lower than those for other drugs and that the
FDA was acting to cope with a significant backlog. Both impressions would
be incorrect. The principal intent of the cancer initiatives announced
this past March is to accelerate the availability of new drugs for
patients with cancers refractory to currently available treatments;
achieving this goal will not compromise the FDA's standards for
effectiveness and safety of new drugs. Furthermore, there has been no
recent backlog of marketing applications for cancer drugs at the FDA; in
the past several years, all applications submitted to the Division of
Oncology Drug Products have been processed on or ahead of the timelines
set forth by Congress in 1992.

<P><I>ROBERT J. DELAP Director, Division of Oncology Drug Products Food and Drug
Administration</I>

<HR><CENTER><B>SCREENING FOR PROSTATE CANCER</B></CENTER>

<P>The outstanding article by Gerald E. Hanks and Peter T. Scardino ["Does
Screening for Prostate Cancer Make Sense?"] omits mention of the
reproducibility and false interpretations of tests measuring
prostate-specific antigen (PSA). It is known that the condition
prostatitis can lead to elevated scores, for example, but there is no
information on how unrelated illnesses can also cause dramatic rises. I
took a PSA test recently when I visited the hospital because of a stomach
ailment. The score had jumped from my normal level of five to 43. I chose
a repeat test rather than a biopsy. In a week my score had dropped to
22-still a troubling result. But being a physicist, I theorized that the
numbers would fall exponentially with time. Repeated measurements showed
this precise behavior, and after four weeks my score returned to normal,
where it has remained ever since.

<P><I>SHERMAN FRANKEL Professor Emeritus University of Pennsylvania</I>

<P><HR><I>Letters selected for publication may be edited for length and clarity.</I>

<P><HR SIZE=4>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

