<P><A NAME="author"><HR><B>The Authors</B></A>
<P>JEFFREY S. KARGEL and <A HREF="http://www.lpl.arizona.edu/grad/academic/faculty/strom.html">ROBERT G. STROM</A> have worked together on various projects
in planetary science for over a decade. Kargel met Strom soon after beginning
graduate studies at the University of Arizona, where he received a doctorate in
planetary sciences in 1990. Kargel remained at the University of Arizona's Lunar
and Planetary Science Laboratory for two years doing postdoctoral research on the
icy moons of the outer solar system and then joined the U.S. Geological Survey's
astrogeology group in Flagstaff. Strom began his career working as a petroleum
geologist, but he became involved in lunar exploration efforts during the 1960s
and joined the faculty of the University of Arizona, where he continues to teach
and conduct research. He has participated on National Aeronautics and Space
Administration science teams assembled for the Apollo program, for the Mariner
missions to Venus and Mercury, and for the Voyager missions to the outer solar
system.
